TY  - JOUR
AU  - Berman, Eli
AU  - Bound, John
AU  - Griliches, Zvi
T1  - Changes in the Demand for Skilled Labor within U. S. Manufacturing: Evidence from the Annual Survey of Manufactures*
PY  - 1994
Y1  - 1994/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118467
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 109
IS  - 2
SP  - 367
EP  - 397
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper investigates the shift in demand away from unskilled and toward skilled labor in U. S. manufacturing over the 1980s. Production labor-saving technological change is the chief explanation for this shift. That conclusion is based on three facts: (1) the shift is due mostly to increased use of skilled workers within the 450 industries in U. S. manufacturing rather than to a reallocation of employment between industries, as would be implied by a shift in product demand due to trade or to a defense buildup; (2) trade- and defense-demand are associated with only small employment reallocation effects; (3) increased use of nonproduction workers is strongly correlated with investment in computers and in R&amp;D.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118467
ER  - 



